Author:  MAHONEY
Vol / Page:  12
Edition:
Quote:  However, there as no direct English 'bush tramway' experience to call upon, and so all the adaptations to bush conditions occurred in the new land...An overseas forester reported in 1877: "The universal use of the tramway forms a marked feature of the treatment of New Zealand forests." <i>Ibid.</i> 78 Steam locomotives designed for normal railways were not suitable for the rugged conditions on bush tramways and gradually special designs evolved. <i>Ibid.</i> 83 1871 Opening of William Brownlee's Mahakipawa-Kaituna valley tramway on 4'0" (1219 mm) gauge. This was New Zealand's first steam-worked bush tramway and used a British 0-4-0 vertical boiler locomotive.
